 1. Introduction - Prosper: advancing financial well-being¶

Prosper was founded in 2005 as the first peer-to-peer lending marketplace in the United States. Since then, Prosper has facilitated more than $18 billion in loans to more than 1,060,000 people.

This time, we have been asked to analyze a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, the original dataset provides in-depth information such as loan amount, borrower's APR and interest-rate, as well as Prosper's rating, current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

2.1. Gathering Data¶

Let's start by downloading the relevant dataset. The file (prosperLoanData.csv) is hosted on Udacity's servers and can be downloaded programmatically using the requests library and this URL.

Having taken a quick look at the data, we can now list the following issues that deserve some attention:

Tidiness issues¶

  • 1. Choose subset of important features
  • 2. Merge CreditGrade (before 2009) and ProsperRating(Alpha) (after 2009) and drop other irrelevant columns
  • 3. Fill in missing values of Occupation ('unknown')
  • 4. Convert CreditScoreRangeLower and CreditScoreRangeUpper into a single CreditScore value (calculate average of the two variables)

Quality issues¶

  • 5. Remove rows with null on DebtToIncomeRatio

Looking at Graphs 19 and 20, we can see that as the income increases, the percentage of loans being defaulted decreases. This is somewhat expected as people with larger income, in general, would have more means to pay back their loans.

It is also worthy noting that the second tier of income (\$25000-\\$49999) is the one which contributes the most with defaulted loans. This, however, may be explained by the mere fact that most borrowers fall under this income range.

Also important to mention that, altough they contribute much less to the absolute number of defaulted loans, the first tier of income (< \$25000) is the one which, proportionally, defaults the most.

That being said, those earning under \$50000 per year deserve some further investigation.

Ok! Before we consider these last two graphs, it's time to sum up our finds on LoanStatus:

  • Graph 13 tells us that Prosper has the vast majority of its issued loans current;
  • Graphs 14 to 18 point to an unexpected direction. It might be the case that, somewhat surprisingly, EmploymentStatusDuration, DebtToIncomeRation, BankcardUtilization do not have a significant influence on someone defaulting on a loan. That is, one would have thought that the likelihood of someone defaulting should increase proportionally to that person's debt (BankCardUtilization) and/or debt ratio (DebtToIncomeRation). But, no!
  • Graphs 19 and 20, on their turn, seem to show an inverted relationship between IncomeRange and LoanStatus. That is, as income increases, the percentage of loans being defaulted decreases.
    • Also, the second tier of income (\$25000-\\$49999) is the one which contributes the most with defaulted loans, whereas the first tier of income (< \$25000) is the one which, proportionally, defaults the most.
  • Graph 21 and 22, similarly to graphs 14 to 18, also pointed to a surprisingly direction: small loans (~\$4000) are more likely then any other to be defaulted.
  • Graph 23, focusing on the 3 most common loan amounts (\$4000, \\$10000 and \$15000), revealed the relationship between loan size and income range for defaulted loans. That's to say, the majority of small loans have been requested by people earning between \\$25000 and \$49999. Also, specifically for those earning less than \\$25000, small loans have been disproportionally defaulted.
  • On graph 24, as one would expect, as BorrowerAPR increases, also does the incidence of default.

Taking all of that into consideration, graphs 25 and 26 seem to summarize quite well our findings on LoanStatus:

  • Lower income (below \$50000 per year), when paired with higher levels of BorrowerAPR (above *0.25*), seem to be related to higher levels of default. That is particularly acute for smaller loans (around \\$4000) which make up the vast majority of loans issued by Prosper.

back to top

Conclusions

After reviewing the information available in this analysis, one could come to the following conclusions:

  • Prosper has had an accelerating growth year-on-year (except for a slowdown in 2012). However, with the available data, we still don't know how well Prosper is doing in comparison to its competitors;

  • Not surprisingly, on average, the larger the loan amount, larger the monthly payment. Those, on their turn, tend to coalesce into 3 clearly distinct groups, driven by the loan term;

  • Of the most common loan sizes (\$4000, \\$10000 and \$15000), Prosper's portifolio seems to lean heavely on the first one. Also, most of its customers seem to earn under \\$50000;

  • Lower income (below \$50000 per year), when paired with higher levels of BorrowerAPR (above 0.25), seem to be related to higher levels of default. Given the insight above, it could be in the best interest of Prosper to develop a reliable model in predicting when this profile of customer would tend to default.
